# Orchestrator run routing

Apply this rule when the user asks for multi-agent automation, an
`orchestrator agent`, sequential workloads, a roadmap-driven execution pass, or
uses the legacy phrase `run automation`.

## Canonical source

- Read `.cursor/orchestrator/PROTOCOL.md` for the full workflow.
- Use `.cursor/skills/orchestrator-run/SKILL.md` as the first context layer for this flow.
- Treat `.cursor/automation/PROTOCOL.md` as a legacy redirect only.

## Storage rules

- New run artifacts belong in `.cursor/orchestrator/run/<YYYY-MM-DD>-<slug>/`.
- Do not create new outputs in `.cursor/automation/runs/`.
- Keep completed dated folders under `run/`; that folder is the archive.

## Required artifacts

Every orchestrator run should maintain:

- `ROADMAP.md`
- `ORCHESTRATOR_LOG.md`
- optional `track-plans/` when the run is broad enough for a middle coordination layer
- workload files in `workloads/`
- per-agent logs in `agent-logs/`
- per-step verification notes in `verification/`
- `FINAL_SWEEP.md`
- `FINAL_REPORT.md`

## Execution rules

- Default to sequential agents unless the user explicitly wants parallel work.
- Prefer a three-tier model (`orchestrator` -> `track plans` -> micro-workloads) when it reduces repeated full-context prompts.
- Validate each workload before starting the next one.
- Let the orchestrator agent apply small follow-up fixes between workloads when needed.
- End with a final sweep for dead code, ghost routes, stale files, and documentation drift.
